Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

gun_data.csv¶

This data is the number of firearm checks by month, state, and type that are called into the FBI's National Instant Criminal Background Check System. Gun shops use the system to verify customers' eligibility for buying guns.

One big point to note is that these numbers represent gun background checks, not sales, and a 1:1 correlation cannot be made between the two.

The main columns included in the dataset are:

  • month - The year and month data was collected for
  • state - The US state data is being collected on
  • totals - The total number of background checks for that month and state

The totals are then broken down into both type of check that is being done and the gun type the check is being done for. The types of checks are:

  • Non-Specified - Checks initiated by an officially-licensed Federal Firearms Licensee (FFL) or criminal justice/law enforcement agency prior to the issuance of a firearm-related permit or transfer.
  • Pre-Pawn - Checks requested by an officially-licensed FFL on prospective firearm transferees seeking to pledge or pawn a firearm as security for the payment or repayment of money, prior to actually pledging or pawning the firearm.
  • Redemption - Checks requested by an officially-licensed FFL on prospective firearm transferees attempting to regain possession of a firearm after pledging or pawning a firearm as security at a pawn shop.
  • Returned/Disposition - Checks requested by criminal justice/law enforcement agencies prior to returning a firearm in its possession to the respective transferee, to ensure the individual is not prohibited.
  • Rentals - Checks requested by an officially-licensed FFL on prospective firearm transferees attempting to possess a firearm when the firearm is loaned or rented for use off the premises of the business.
  • Private Sale - Checks requested by an officially-licensed FFL on prospective firearm transferees attempting to possess a firearm from a private party seller who is not an officially-licensed FFL.
  • Return to Seller - Checks requested by an officially-licensed FFL on prospective firearm transferees attempting to possess a firearm from a private party seller who is not an officially-licensed FFL.

And the types of guns are:

  • Handgun - Any firearm which has a short stock and is designed to be held and fired by the use of a single hand; and (b) any combination of parts from which a firearm described in paragraph (a) can be assembled.
  • Long Gun - A weapon designed or redesigned, made or remade, and intended to be fired from the shoulder, and designed or redesigned and made or remade to use the energy of the explosive in (a) a fixed metallic cartridge to fire a single projectile through a rifled bore for each single pull of the trigger; or (b) a fixed shotgun shell to fire through a smooth bore either a number of ball shot or a single projectile for each single pull of the trigger.
  • Other - Refers to frames, receivers, and other firearms that are neither handguns nor long guns (rifles or shotguns), such as firearms having a pistol grip that expel a shotgun shell, or National Firearms Act firearms, including silencers.

US_Census_Data.csv¶

This is US Census Data straight from the United States Census Bureau. It contains several census variables broken out by state. While no direct link to the gun_data.csv, both data sets are provided on a state level meaning the census data can supplement the gun data for additional investigation.

The data is organized with the state names as the columns, and the census variables as rows.

Question(s) for Analysis¶

Question 1:¶

Does the sitting President's political party, have an effect on the number of background checks being run for guns?

Question 2:¶

Are there any state demographics that effect the number of background checks being run for guns?

Data Cleaning¶

According to the nics_df.info(), there are null values in all count values besides multiple and total. My intuition would be that the nulls are all meant to be zeroes, but to make sure, I will add all the columns up (excluding the nulls) and compare them to the total. If they are equal, then the nulls would be zero.

I'll start off by replacing all the nulls with zeros, then confirming there are no nulls.

I now need to create a function that looks at the date of the row, then, in a new column titled pres_party, outputs either Republican or Democrat.

In [13]:
def presidential_party(row):
    if row >= pd.to_datetime('2017-01-20'):
        return 'Republican'
    elif row >= pd.to_datetime('2009-01-20'):
        return 'Democrat'
    elif row >= pd.to_datetime('2001-01-20'):
        return 'Republican'
    elif row >= pd.to_datetime('1993-01-20'):
        return 'Democrat'

nics_df['pres_party'] = nics_df['month'].apply(presidential_party)

# This function takes a string, a character(s) you want to replace, and the character(s) you want to replace it with, and

# This function creates a dictionary of columns and a dtype to change all the column dtypes to.
def dict_maker(columns, type_name):
    converts = {}
    for col in columns:
        converts[col] = type_name
    return converts

convert_int32 = dict_maker(census_16.iloc[:, [0,1,-1,-2]], 'int32')

The last thing regarding this question that I want to look at before moving on is, how the component of time may have played a factor in these results. Since the last nine years of this data included 8 with a sitting Democratic president, if gun background checks were naturally going up as time went on, this would increase the average for Democrats.

So, to get an idea of how gun background checks changed over time, I will plot the total checks done for each month on a line graph.

Whether it was the incoming President's political party or another factor that caused the gun background checks to increase, is unable to be answered with the data at hand.

Research Question 2¶

Are there any state demographics that effect the number of background checks being run for guns?¶

I want to take a look at the relationships between the demographic categories and total gun background checks. Since I don't need to compare every category to each other, I won't use the scatterplot matrix. Instead, I'll run a quick function to plot each category against the 'totals' column.

In [48]:
for col in gun_census.iloc[:,:-1]:
    gun_census.plot(col,'totals', kind='scatter');

The first two graphs show a positive relationship between the total gun background checks and their variables. Intuitively, this makes sense as those variables are both population estimates. It tracks that more people in a state would mean a greater likelihood of more gun background checks.

Also, the last two graphs seem to have a positive relationship as well. These are the Housing Units and Building Permits variables. But my guess would be that these are positively related to the population of the states, as more people would likely mean needing more housing units and more building permits.

But, I can take a look at the relationship of those 4 variables to confirm.

Conclusions¶

Question 1¶

Between November 1998 and September 2017, on average, nearly 60% more gun background checks were run a month when a Democratic president was in office versus a Republican one.

While this is a large difference, it is ultimately an area that has not been fully explored in this research. There are a myriad of other variables that could be in play regarding the relationship. This include things like geopolitical relations, changes in background check requirements, and personal presidential convictions not held specifically by one's political party. All of which does not have data included in this anaylsis, representing one of the limitations of this research.

Question 2¶

After looking through the relationships between multiple state demographics and total gun background checks for 2016, there doesn't appear to be any strong relationships.

This topic could be more thoroughly researched by performing true statistical analysis via regressions. The lack of this type of exploration is a limitation of this analysis.
